uined, triggering the worst commercial crisis in British India up to that time. This book, the first major study of a British agency house in India, presents an account of both of Palmer's business and personal life, showing how his personal relations and circumstances shaped his commercial strategies, with ultimately disastrous consequences for Anglo-Indian relations as well as his clients. ANTHONY WEBSTER is Head of Humanities at the University of Central Lancashire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBritishzIndiavBiography. 0aColonial companieszIndia. 0aMerchantszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aMerchantszIndiavBiography. 4aEighteenth Century Studies. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Modern / General.2bisacsh  aBritish India.  aBritish imperialism.  aBritish merchant.  aJohn Palmer.  acommercial firm.  aopium trade.  aplantation agriculture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615589540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846155895423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846155895/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles